Soybean farmers in  Brazil , set to
surpass the U.S. as the largest grower of the oilseed, will
harvest a record crop of as much as 82.8 million metric tons in
the 2012-2013 season, the government said.  The harvest in year that started Sept. 1 is expected to
rise from 66.4 million tons collected in the past season, the
 Agriculture Ministry â€™s crop-forecasting agency, known as Conab,
said in its first report for the current crop year.  Corn output is forecast at as much as 73.2 million tons,
compared with 72.6 million in the previous season, Conab said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
